rm
To delete files, you use the rm command, which stands for remove.

Bash
rm apple
You can also delete multiple files at once by separating their names with spaces:

Bash
rm apple banana carrot
Important Behavior & Crucial Flags
Unlike a graphical user interface (like Windows Recycle Bin or macOS Trash), rm does not send files to a temporary trash folder. Once you hit enter on an rm command, the filesystem unlinks the file pointer instantly. For all practical purposes, the file is permanently gone.

To handle directories or change how the command runs, you rely on these key flags:

rm -r (Recursive): This is mandatory if you want to delete a directory that contains files or subfolders. It tells the terminal to descend into the folder hierarchy, delete all inner files first, and then remove the parent folder.

Bash
rm -r fruits
rm -v (Verbose): Prints a visual log to your screen for every single file or directory as it is removed. This gives you concrete feedback on what just happened.

rm -f (Force): Overrides minor write-protection prompts and completely ignores nonexistent files without throwing an error message.

rm -i (Interactive): Plays it safe. The terminal will explicitly ask you for confirmation (y/n) before destroying a file. It is highly recommended if you are deleting files using wildcards (like rm -i *.log).

Combining Flags for Maximum Power (And Risk)
rm -rv: Deletes a directory recursively while printing out a step-by-step confirmation of everything it is removing.

rm -rf: The nuclear option. It combines recursive and force behavior to instantly and silently vaporize a folder structure without asking a single question, even if files are marked as read-only. Always double-check your path before executing this.